			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think this idea has been tossed around once or twice, but I'd like to get some input on it. One ot the funtions of the LoY expansion was the map system. Now, maps in a game can be both good and bad. If all maps are present right when you first log onto the game, I think this lowers the exploration factor in a game. If the maps start off mostly blank and never update, such as it is now in EQ, then the usefulness of the function is not there. I know I could just go to the numerous websites out there and just download all the maps, but I don't like that idea. Why should we have to go out of our way to get a function to work correctly in a game that we pay for? 
<br />

<br />
What I'd like to see SOE go to is a type of Map Quest System. Here are two options that I have thought of, feel free to add more, or just discuss the good or bad of each.
<br />

<br />
Trial by fire: The only maps that are present in game at character creation is the map of the home town and the noob area(s) surrounding their city. After that, all maps update as the adventurer travels through any new zone. It could be something on the lines of "anything the player sees, the map records". With this method, if an adventurer is walking in a zone that has a house, the outside of the house is update on the map as the character walks near it, but not inside of the house unless they go inside.
<br />

<br />
Find the map parts: This method witll help put some of the quest back into Everquest. Basically, you quest for parts of a map (these are no drop) and combine them in a container to reveal the entire map, this map is then given to the Map NPC Quest-giver and the map file is update for that zone. These pieces could be dropped in zones for your level, but creat maps for zones you will explore next. Example: Assling Ranger starts off in Rivervale (Rivervale map is the only map in their system) and talks to Map NPC Quest Giver and is given clues as to where parts of the Misty Thicket map have been last seen, i.e. "lost. These could be ground spawns and what not. Collect these pieces and combine in container, give to quest giver, next time you zone into the Thicket, your map is available.
<br />

<br />
What do you all think of this?
<br />

<br />
Gwondar Theburninator
<br />
55 Outrider
<br />
The Tribunal</span><span class="gentblsmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
